05559nam a22007815i 9781787446762DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202020xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97817874467627 a10.1515/97817874467622doi  a(DE-B1597)674748  a(OCoLC)1420506997  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 4aPT143.P3bG75 2020eb 7aLIT0041702bisacsh04a830.9/36090332231 aGriffiths, Elystan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Shepherd, the ‹I›Volk‹/I›, and the Middle Class :bTransformations of Pastoral in German-Language Writing, 1750-1850 /cElystan Griffiths.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2020] 1bCamden House, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (300 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in German Literature Linguistics and Culture ;v21000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Translations -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction: Pastoral as a Way of Not Looking at the Country -- t1: Pastoral in the Enlightenment: Salomon Gessner’s Idylls -- t2: “Wo giebts dann Schäfer wie diese?”: Friedrich “Maler” Müller’s Idylls of Cultural Renewal -- t3: Johann Heinrich Voss’s Experiments with an Enlightened Idyll -- t4: Goethe and Schiller’s Engagements with Pastoral: Facing the Postrevolutionary World -- t5: Heinrich von Kleist: The Promises and Illusions of Pastoral -- t6: Pastoral in the Age of Capital: Eduard Mörike and Johann Nestroy -- tConclusion: From Middle-Class Critique to Critiquing the Middle Classes -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAnalyzes the transformation of German-language pastoral from a portrayal of the idyllic lives of herdsmen into a vehicle for the concerns and aspirations of the middle class.European pastoral tradition traces its roots to Theocritus's Idylls and Virgil's Eclogues, which portrayed herdsmen pursuing love and art. While the lives of shepherds, or of country folk generally, remain the ostensible subject of pastoral, Elystan Griffiths argues that in the German context after 1750 its central concerns were those of an emergent, nationally minded, creative middle class. These concerns became increasingly urgent in the face of the upheaval of the French Revolution and the need to respond to the rise of capitalist modernity. The Shepherd, the Volk, and the Middle Class traces how pastoral was transformed in the work of major German-language authors, including Gessner, "Maler" Müller, J. H. Voss, Goethe, Kleist, Mörike, and Nestroy, into a vehicle for serious moral, political, and social questions. Debates raged about whether present-day shepherds were fit to appear in literature, or whether the objects of pastoral should, rather, be the idealized shepherds of Arcadian prehistory or early Biblical times. Pastoral was thus bound up with cultural and political questions surrounding the relationships between the classes, the state of the peasantry, the nature of art, and most fundamentally the social constraints of the thinking subject amid the emancipatory promise of the Enlightenment. Elystan Griffithsis Senior Lecturer in German at the University of Birmingham. He has published extensively on late eighteenth- and early nineteenth century literature, particularly on La Roche, Lenz, and Kleist.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCountry life in literature. 0aGerman literaturexHistory and criticismy18th century. 0aGerman literaturexHistory and criticismy19th century. 0aMiddle class in literature. 0aPastoral literature, GermanxHistory and criticism. 4aEighteenth Century Studies. 4aGerman History. 4aGerman Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh